Incident Response > [T3]: Lab - Suricata: Write a custom signature to alert on traffic

Write a custom signature to alert on traffic

A Suricata's signature consists of three parts:

  1. Action: determines what happens when the signature matches
  2. Header: defining the protocol, IP addresses, ports, and direction of the rule.
  3. Options: defining the specifics of the rule.

alert http any any -> any any (msg:"VPNFilter malware User-Agent"; content:"Mozilla/6.1 (compatible|3B| MSIE 9.0|3B| Windows NT 5.3|3B| Trident/5.0)"; http_user_agent; sid:2; rev:1;) 

In the above rule, you will see the Action as alert, the Header as http any any -> any any and the rest of the rule is the Options part.

In this demo, we will be writing a rule that detects traffic to a specific host, and to do this, we will need to create a custom rule using an editor:

sudo vim /var/lib/suricata/rules/local.rules 

And place the rule content:

alert http any any -> any any (msg:"CCD test HTTP Host"; content:"cyberdefenders.org"; endswith; http_host; sid:1000000; rev:1;)
Update the suricata.yaml to include the newly created rule.

- local.rules

Reload Suricata rules by executing:

sudo kill -USR2 $(pidof suricata) 

Now we can test our rule by tailing the Suricata's fast.log and visiting www.cyberdefenders.org 

sudo tail -n0 -f /var/log/suricata/fast.log
